0":"1180","1202":"1202","1278":"1278","Abt 1177":"circa 1177","1177":"1177","1219":"1219","Abt 1190":"circa 1190","Samlesbury, Lancastershire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Samlesbury, Lancashire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1177–Aft 1219":"about 1177–after 1219","1177–1219":"1177–1219","1180–1191":"1180–1191","1202–1278":"1202–1278","1177–Female":"1177–Deceased","1190–1275":"1190–1275","1150–1191":"1150–1191","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1190":"1190","1275":"1275","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","Aft 1219":"after 1219","1191":"1191","1180":"1180","1202":"1202","1278":"1278","Abt 1177":"about 1177","1177":"1177","1219":"1219","Abt 1190":"about 1190","Samlesbury, Lancastershire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Samlesbury, Lancashire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Croft","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places, for example in Lincolnshire, Lancashire, Herefordshire, and North Yorkshire, all named with Old English <i>croft</i> ‘small arable enclosure (normally adjoining a house)’, or a topographic name for someone who lived by a croft, from Middle English <i>croft</i>.","English: possibly in some cases a variant of   Craft   2.","Americanized form of German, Danish, Swedish, or Jewish   Kraft  . Compare   Kroft   and   Craft  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Craft","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>craft</i> ‘skillful, clever, learned’.","English: habitational name from Croft in Leicestershire. See also   Croft  .","Americanized form of German, Danish, Swedish, or Jewish   Kraft  . See also   Croft  ."]},{"name":"Crate","meanings":["English (Hampshire and Surrey): from Middle English <i>crate</i> ‘hurdle, basket’, or occasionally perhaps from <i>crete</i> ‘cradle’, probably applied as a metonymic occupational name for a maker of such articles. Alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Croft   1."]},{"name":"Crofts","meanings":["English: variant of   Croft  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Groft","meanings":["English: perhaps an altered form of   Croft  ."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert de Croft was born about 1177, in Samlesbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hugh de Croft II, was 28 and his mother, Mrs. Hugh de Croft II, was 19. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Gilbert de Croft. He died after 1219."},"et":{"Abt 1177–Aft 1219":"umbes 1177–pärast 1219","1177–1219":"1177–1219","1180–1191":"1180–1191","1202–1278":"1202–1278","1177–Female":"1177–Surnud","1190–1275":"1190–1275","1150–1191":"1150–1191","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1190":"1190","1275":"1275","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","Aft 1219":"pärast 1219","1191":"1191","1180":"1180","1202":"1202","1278":"1278","Abt 1177":"umbes 1177","1177":"1177","1219":"1219","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190","Samlesbury, Lancastershire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Samlesbury, Lancashire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1177–Aft 1219":"noin 1177–1219 jälkeen","1177–1219":"1177–1219","1180–1191":"1180–1191","1202–1278":"1202–1278","1177–Female":"1177–Kuollut","1190–1275":"1190–1275","1150–1191":"1150–1191","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1275":"1275","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","Aft 1219":"1219 jälkeen","1191":"1191","1180":"1180","1202":"1202","1278":"1278","Abt 1177":"noin 1177","1177":"1177","1219":"1219","Abt 1190":"noin 1190","Samlesbury, Lancastershire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Samlesbury, Lancashire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1177–Aft 1219":"environ 1177–après 121